feat: Comprehensive overhaul of UI, features, and bug fixes

This commit addresses a wide range of user feedback, including critical bug fixes, a full theme system implementation, and significant UI/UX enhancements, reflecting a proactive partnership approach.

- **Critical Bug Fixes:**
  - **Search Panel Crash:** Fixed a crash caused by undefined text in search results by adding a guard clause.
  - **Audio Player UI:** Corrected a visibility bug where controls were invisible on a white background by applying a theme-based accent color to the player.

- **Theme System Overhaul:**
  - **Dark Mode:** Re-introduced a full-featured Dark Mode for eye comfort.
  - **Default Theme:** Set the default theme to Sepia as requested.
  - **Consistent Theming:** Replaced all instances of hardcoded colors (e.g., #8b7355) with CSS variables (`var(--color-accent)`) across all components and styles. This ensures that changing the theme now applies consistently across the entire application.
  - **Refined Palettes:** Adjusted the color palettes for Sepia, Green, and Dark themes to be more aesthetically pleasing and have better contrast.

- **UI/UX Enhancements:**
  - **Verse Context Menu:** Implemented a new on-click context menu for each verse, providing options for Listen, Bookmark, Share, Tafsir, and Translation.
  - **Default Layout:** The default reading layout is now 'flow' mode (continuous text), with the option to toggle to 'list' mode.
  - **Font Size Control:** Re-implemented the font size control in the Settings page, which now correctly affects both list and flow layouts.
  - **Chapter Headers:** Redesigned the Surah headers to be more prominent and visually appealing.

- **Bug Fixes (from previous iterations):**
  - **Tafsir/Translation:** Ensured data fetching is correct by making settings apply instantly and providing a translation selector.
  - **Search Panel Data:** The backend now enriches search results with full verse details, fixing incorrect descriptions and navigation.

performed_via_github_app.description:
### Socket protects your app from malicious dependencies lurking in your open source supply chain.

Open source code makes up 90% of most codebases. It is critical to manage it effectively to reduce your security risk.

## Detect and block open source supply chain attacks

Security teams depend on Socket to prevent malicious open source dependencies from infiltrating their apps.

Socket dramatically improves your open source security posture by _detecting and blocking the attacks you don't expect_ ‚Äì malware, install scripts, hidden code, typo-squatting, and more ‚Äì which aren't caught by traditional vulnerability scanners.

- **Block malware** ‚Äì Block emerging malware threats

- **Block typo-squatting** ‚Äì Block malicious packages that differ in name by only a few characters, and recommend the correct package

- **Detect hidden code** ‚Äì Detect obfuscated, minified, or hidden code

- **Detect privileged API usage** ‚Äì Report when a dependency update introduces new risky API usage ‚Äì filesystem, network, child_process, eval()

- **Detect suspicious updates** ‚Äì Sudden inclusion of privileged APIs in patch or minor releases

Socket currently [supports 60 detections](https://socket.dev/npm/issue) in 5 categories: supply chain risk, quality, maintenance, known vulnerabilities, and license problems.

## Take charge of your dependency health

Socket improves security outcomes and reduces work for security teams by **surfacing actionable security information directly inline in GitHub** so developers are empowered to make better decisions.

- **Five minute deployment** ‚Äì The easiest security product you'll ever deploy in your organization. Just install a GitHub app and you're done.

- **Provide security feedback directly on PRs** ‚Äì Empower developers to solve security issues before they're deployed into production.

- **Automated security** ‚Äì Spend security team resources auditing the highest-impact dependencies, instead of all or nothing.

## Socket detects what vulnerability scanners can‚Äôt

It's no longer sufficient to scan for known vulnerabilities (CVEs) and stop there. And yet, that's what the leading "supply chain security" products do, leaving you vulnerable.

It can take weeks or months for a CVE to be discovered, reported, and detected by tools. But in today's culture of fast development, a malicious dependency can be updated, merged, and running in production in days or even sometimes hours.

Defenders need a new approach to address emerging threats from malicious dependencies:

- **Maintainer intentionally added malware** ‚Äì Rogue maintainer sabotaged his own open source package with 100M downloads/month, affecting companies such as Amazon AWS

- **Package hijacked and poisoned w/ cryptominers and password-stealing malware** ‚Äì Deliberate malware introduced into multiple packages with 30M downloads/month each

- **Package hijacked to add backdoor targeting a specific organization** ‚Äì Obfuscated malware added to a dependency which targeted a single company, went undetected for over a week, and made it into their production build

- **NPM package manager allowed anyone to publish new versions of any package** ‚Äì Attackers could publish new versions of any NPM package without authorization _for multiple years_

Using third-party dependencies without proper vetting leaves you open to hacking, breaches, and assorted security misfortune.
